Builder pattern:
The Problem It Solves: 
Imagine you want to create a Car object. A car can have:
An engine type (e.g., V6, V8, Electric)

A number of seats

Optional features like a sunroof

If you use a constructor with parameters, it might look like this:
Car car = new Car("V8", 4, true);
This works, but it’s not very clear what each argument means. 
If you add more options, the constructor becomes long and confusing (called a telescoping constructor problem).
// Product class
class Car {
    private String engine;
    private int seats;
    private boolean sunroof;

    // Private constructor to enforce use of Builder
    private Car(CarBuilder builder) {
        this.engine = builder.engine;
        this.seats = builder.seats;
        this.sunroof = builder.sunroof;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Car with " + engine + " engine, " + seats + " seats, sunroof: " + sunroof;
    }

    // Builder class
    public static class CarBuilder {
        private String engine;
        private int seats;
        private boolean sunroof;

        public CarBuilder setEngine(String engine) {
            this.engine = engine;
            return this; // allows chaining
        }

        public CarBuilder setSeats(int seats) {
            this.seats = seats;
            return this;
        }

        public CarBuilder setSunroof(boolean sunroof) {
            this.sunroof = sunroof;
            return this;
        }

        public Car build() {
            return new Car(this);
        }
    }
}

// Client code
public class BuilderExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car car = new Car.CarBuilder()
                        .setEngine("V8")
                        .setSeats(4)
                        .setSunroof(true)
                        .build();

        System.out.println(car);
    }
}

4 parts:
a. Product - the complext obj thet we want to create
b. Builder - Provides interface(not java interface) for creating parts of the product
c. Concrete Builder - If your builder is an interface then this concrete builder is just it's implementation
d. Director - Uses the builder to construct obj

The constructr of the product class should be private
Write the builder class as inner class and static
Write setter methods in the inner builder class 
So, The builder can directly access the private fields of the outer class.
This avoids exposing setters in the product class itself, keeping the product immutable after construction.
As an inner class, it’s clear that the builder belongs only to Car and isn’t meant to be reused elsewhere.

The cient code is the 'Builder Driver'